#Approach:

💡 IDEA
- Direct simulation karna mushkil hai:
  "Card 1 bahar aaye, phir Card 2, phir Card 3..."

- Isliye reverse socho:

  "Card i ko kis position par rakhna chahiye
   taaki simulation me wo i-th card bankar nikle?"

- Queue positions maintain karegi.
- Har step par ek index choose karenge aur waha current card place kar denge.

⚙️ APPROACH
1. Queue me saare indices daal do.

   q = [0,1,2,3,...]

2. Card i (1 → N) ke liye:

   a) Queue ko i times rotate karo.
      front → rear

   b) Front index nikalo.

   c) ans[index] = i

3. End me ans array hi required deck arrangement hai.

📝 EXAMPLE

N = 4

Initially:

Indices Queue

[0,1,2,3]

--------------------------------

i = 1

Rotate 1 time

[1,2,3,0]

Take front

index = 1

ans[1] = 1

Queue:
[2,3,0]

--------------------------------

i = 2

Rotate 2 times

[0,2,3]

Take front

index = 0

ans[0] = 2

Queue:
[2,3]

--------------------------------

i = 3

Rotate 3 times

[3,2]

Take front

index = 3

ans[3] = 3

Queue:
[2]

--------------------------------

i = 4

Rotate 4 times

[2]

Take front

index = 2

ans[2] = 4

Final:

[2,1,4,3]

✅ Answer

❓ WHY QUEUE
- Question me continuously front element rear me move ho raha hai.
- Queue exactly isi behavior ko represent karti hai.

Operations:

poll()  -> front remove
offer() -> rear insert

Queue rotation = card rotation

⏱️ COMPLEXITY
Time  : O(N²)

Reason:
- For card i,
  i rotations kar rahe hain.

Total:

1 + 2 + 3 + ... + N

= O(N²)

Space : O(N)

- Queue
- Answer Array

🎯 INTERVIEW POINT
- Sabse important observation:

  Hum actual cards simulate nahi kar rahe.

  Hum positions simulate kar rahe hain.

- Queue stores indices, not card values.

- Jab index milta hai:

  ans[index] = current card

- Reverse construction technique hai:
  Pehle se decide kar rahe hain ki card 1,2,3... kis position par hone chahiye.

- Queue Rotation + Position Assignment
  = Complete Solution.

#Code:

import java.util.*;

public class Solution{
    
    public ArrayList<Integer> rotation(int n){
      //You can code here

      int[] ans = new int[n];
      Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();

      for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
        q.offer(i);
      }

      for(int i=1; i<=n; i++){
        //Step-1: rotate queue i times
        for(int j=1; j<=i; j++){
          q.offer(q.poll());
        }

        //Step-2: peek index is the index where the current element will be stored in the new array
        int index = q.poll();
        ans[index] = i;
      }

      ArrayList<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
      for(int num : ans){
        result.add(num);
      }

      return result;
       
   }
}
